[Transaction.success](https://neo4j.com/docs/java-reference/current/javadocs/org/neo4j/graphdb/Transaction.html#success--) only *marks* a transaction as successful. The transaction is not actually committed until [Transaction.close()](https://neo4j.com/docs/java-reference/current/javadocs/org/neo4j/graphdb/Transaction.html#close--) is called.

The [Transaction](https://neo4j.com/docs/java-reference/current/javadocs/org/neo4j/graphdb/Transaction.html) JavaDocs states the following:
&gt; Here&#39;s the idiomatic use of programmatic transactions in Neo4j
&gt; starting from java 7:
&gt; 
&gt;     try ( Transaction tx = graphDb.beginTx() )  {
&gt;         // operations on the graph
&gt;         // ...
&gt; 
&gt;         tx.success();
&gt;     }

That idiom uses a [try-with-resources](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/exceptions/tryResourceClose.html) statement to ensure that `tx.close()` will be called automatically when the statement is exited (even if due to an exception). Your transactional code should follow suit.

